	  <title>Self Test: Distance Preserving Linear Maps</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>For each of the statements below indicate whether it is true or false</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>L\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math> is invertible, then <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ L(\Vect{x}) } = \Abs{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Can you imagine a linear map whose transformation can be reversed, but which fails to preserve all distances?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Consider a dilation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math> by the factor of <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
					          <ol>
						            <li>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Is such a dilation invertible?</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </li>
						            <li>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Is such a dilation length preserving?</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </li>
					          </ol>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We claim that this statement is false. For example, the dilation of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> by the factor <math>
                           <latex>2</latex>
                        </math> is invertible. It's inverse is the contraction with factor <math>
                           <latex>1/2</latex>
                        </math>. By its nature, a dilation with factor two magnifies all distances to twice their original length. But this means that such a dilation is not length preserving.</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore the statement in question is false.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>T\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math> is distance preserving, then <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ T(\Vect{x}) } = \Abs{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Review the definition of a distance preserving linear map.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This statement is verbatim the definition of a distance preserving linear map. So this statement is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>T\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math> is distance preserving, then <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ T(\Vect{y}) - T(\Vect{x}) } = \Abs{ \Vect{y} - \Vect{x} }</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x},\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Recall that <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ \Vect{y} - \Vect{x} }</latex>
                     </math> is the distance from <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We give a conceptual and then a computational answer to this problem.</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>For the conceptual approach, recall that</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <ol>
						               <li>
							                 <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>\Abs{ \Vect{y} - \Vect{x} }</latex>
                              </math> is the distance from <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math> to <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                              </math>, and</para.body>
                        </para>
						               </li>
						               <li>
							                 <para>
                           <para.body>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>\Abs{ T(\Vect{y})- T(\Vect{x}) }</latex>
                              </math> is the distance from <math>
                                 <latex>T(\Vect{x})</latex>
                              </math> to <math>
                                 <latex>T(\Vect{y})</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
						               </li>
					             </ol>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> is distance preserving, this means exactly that these two distances are equal. So the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>For the computational approach we argue as follows</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Abs{ T(\Vect{y}) - T(\Vect{x}) }</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=	</text>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>because <math>
                                          <latex>T</latex>
                                       </math> is linear</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>because <math>
                                          <latex>T</latex>
                                       </math> is linear</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Abs{ T( \Vect{y}-\Vect{x}) }</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=	</text>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Because <math>
                                          <latex>T</latex>
                                       </math> is distance preserving.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Because <math>
                                          <latex>T</latex>
                                       </math> is distance preserving.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Abs{ \Vect{y} - \Vect{x} }</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For every distance preserving <math>
                        <latex>U\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>, it is true that <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ U(1,1,1) } = \sqrt{3}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Compare the length of <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}=(1,1,1)</latex>
                     </math> to the length of <math>
                        <latex>U(\Vect{x}) = U(1,1,1)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}:=(1,1,1)</latex>
                        </math> has length <math>
                           <latex>\Abs{ \Vect{x} } = \sqrt{3}</latex>
                        </math>. A distance preserving linear map preserves this length. Therefore the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>U\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is distance preserving, it is true that <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ U(1,1,1) } = 3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Review the previous problem and its solution.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For every linear <math>
                        <latex>L\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> it is true that <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ L(2,1,-2) }=3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Consider the zero map <math>
                        <latex>L\from \RNr[3] \to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For every invertible linear <math>
                        <latex>K\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> it is true that <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ K(2,1,-2) }=3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Consider the dilation <math>
                        <latex>K\from \RNr[3] \to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>K(\Vect{x}) = 2\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>. – What is <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ K(2,1,-2) }</latex>
                     </math>?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For every distance preserving <math>
                        <latex>R\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> it is true that <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ R(2,1,-2) }=3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>What is the length of <math>
                        <latex>(2,1,-2)</latex>
                     </math>?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Continuing from the previous hint, we find <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ (2,1,-2) } = 3</latex>
                     </math>. If <math>
                        <latex>R</latex>
                     </math> is distance preserving, what is <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ R(2,1,-2) }</latex>
                     </math>?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We find <math>
                           <latex>\Abs{ (2,1,-2) } = 3</latex>
                        </math>. If <math>
                           <latex>R</latex>
                        </math> is distance preserving, then</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\Abs{ R(2,1,-2) } = \Abs{ (2,1,-2) } = 3</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>So, the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>S\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is a shear map with respect to the unit vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                     </math>, then <math>
                        <latex>S(\Vect{x})=\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> for every <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}\bot \Vect{n}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Review the construction of a shear map.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The shear map <math>
                           <latex>S</latex>
                        </math> transforms an arbitrary vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math> into</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>S(\Vect{x})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x} + (\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{n} })\cdot \Vect{n}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                        </math>, and <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{n} } = 0</latex>
                        </math>. So <math>
                           <latex>S(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> in this case. – Therefore the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>S\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is a shear map with respect to the unit vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                     </math>, then <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ S(\Vect{x}) } = \Abs{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
