         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Review the previous problem.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>For each of the statements below indicate whether it is true or false.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The projection of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> onto the hyperspace perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>(1,2,-1)</latex>
                     </math> is invertible.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>This is like saying: ‘If you know that shadow of an object, you can tell all about the shape of the object’. – Is this true?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This projection sends every vector of the form <math>
                           <latex>t\cdot (1,2,-1)</latex>
                        </math> to the <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>-vector. So it can not be invertible. – The statement in question is false.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For <math>
                        <latex>1\leq i\leq n</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>n\geq 2</latex>
                     </math>, the coordinate projection <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{i}\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr</latex>
                     </math> is invertible.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Just consider the projection <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{1}\from \RNr[2] \to \RNr</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{1}(x,y)=x</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Continuing from the previous hint, we have</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Prjctn{1}(1,0)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <text>=</text>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>1</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex/>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <text>=</text>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Prjctn{1}(1,1)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>So if you know that the projection of some point in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> is equal to <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>, can you tell what the point was?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
